Element
FamilyMemberHistory

!FamilyMemberHistory.condition.extension

FamilyMemberHistory.condition.onset[x]

FamilyMemberHistory.patient

!FamilyMemberHistory.status

FamilyMemberHistory.deceased[x]
FamilyMemberHistory.relationship
FamilyMemberHistory.condition.code
FamilyMemberHistory.condition.code is separated from the other FamilyMemberHistory.condition.*

It wasn't running out of memory, pe se -- it's that that the Java process memory limit was bumping up against the container memory limit.
I solved this by taking a few hundred megs _away_ from the Java process.
(see this commit)
hmm. I'll have to invest some time in this...
so I should kick that build off again?
I don't think so -- this was just a config issue.
I was cutting it too close by giving the container only a little bit more memory than the java max heap size.
So when java used all the heap it was allowed to... that wound up triggering the container to kill it.

@Josh Mandel I have an enhancement request for the auto-ig-publisher. We now have a way to template IGs - so that the bulk of the technical content that drives the creation of an ig comes from a separate repo, and the author just writes content.

That's already working now, but my enhancement request is that if someone commits a change to a template to gh, and the auto-ig-publisher gets a notification, instead of building the template like a normal repository, it builds all the igs that depend on the template.

Note: the template is declared in qas.json, so that piece of information is available to the auto-ig-publisher, and it's possible to identify a template as opposed to a regular IG
